[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":319},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F07\u002F26\u002Fjs-core-23-objects-variables-vs-object-properties\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F07\u002F26\u002Fjs-core-23-objects-variables-vs-object-properties\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F07\u002F26\u002Fjs-core-23-objects-variables-vs-object-properties\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F07\u002F26\u002Fjs-core-23-objects-variables-vs-object-properties\u002F":294,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F07\u002F26\u002Fjs-core-23-objects-variables-vs-object-properties\u002F":303},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200726\u002F2777973914\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":276,"date":277,"description":278,"extension":279,"lang":280,"meta":281,"navigation":282,"path":283,"readingMinutes":284,"seo":285,"standalone":286,"stem":287,"tags":288,"tldr":291,"updated":277,"url":292,"__hash__":293},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjs-core-23-objects-variables-vs-object-properties.md","JavaScript Core Concepts (23) — Objects: Variables vs Object Properties","1000807741",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":271},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,32,81,97,150,159,166,193,202,227,243,249,252,256,267],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Let's talk about the difference between variables and object properties.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"the-difference","The difference",[17,25,26,27,31],{},"First thing you probably already know: when you declare a variable, it adds a property under ",[28,29,30],"code",{},"window",".",[33,34,39],"pre",{"className":35,"code":36,"language":37,"meta":38,"style":38},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var a = 1;\nconsole.log(window.a); \u002F\u002F 1\n","js","",[28,40,41,64],{"__ignoreMap":38},[42,43,46,50,54,57,61],"span",{"class":44,"line":45},"line",1,[42,47,49],{"class":48},"sWyjQ","var",[42,51,53],{"class":52},"sMAXC"," a ",[42,55,56],{"class":48},"=",[42,58,60],{"class":59},"sCcAr"," 1",[42,62,63],{"class":52},";\n",[42,65,67,70,74,77],{"class":44,"line":66},2,[42,68,69],{"class":52},"console.",[42,71,73],{"class":72},"sj_SG","log",[42,75,76],{"class":52},"(window.a); ",[42,78,80],{"class":79},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F 1\n",[17,82,83,84,87,88,90,91,93,94,31],{},"But here's something kind of interesting. If you just write ",[28,85,86],{},"b = 2"," (no ",[28,89,49],{},", no declaration at all), you'll find that ",[28,92,30],{}," can still find ",[28,95,96],{},"b",[33,98,100],{"className":35,"code":99,"language":37,"meta":38,"style":38},"var a = 1;\nconsole.log(window.a); \u002F\u002F 1\nb = 2;\nconsole.log(window.b); \u002F\u002F 2\n",[28,101,102,114,124,137],{"__ignoreMap":38},[42,103,104,106,108,110,112],{"class":44,"line":45},[42,105,49],{"class":48},[42,107,53],{"class":52},[42,109,56],{"class":48},[42,111,60],{"class":59},[42,113,63],{"class":52},[42,115,116,118,120,122],{"class":44,"line":66},[42,117,69],{"class":52},[42,119,73],{"class":72},[42,121,76],{"class":52},[42,123,80],{"class":79},[42,125,127,130,132,135],{"class":44,"line":126},3,[42,128,129],{"class":52},"b ",[42,131,56],{"class":48},[42,133,134],{"class":59}," 2",[42,136,63],{"class":52},[42,138,140,142,144,147],{"class":44,"line":139},4,[42,141,69],{"class":52},[42,143,73],{"class":72},[42,145,146],{"class":52},"(window.b); ",[42,148,149],{"class":79},"\u002F\u002F 2\n",[17,151,152,153,155,156,158],{},"So ",[28,154,96],{}," was never created through a proper declaration, yet it still shows up under ",[28,157,30],{},". The biggest difference between these two ways of creating things is this: a real variable can't be deleted.",[17,160,161,162,165],{},"For example, we can use the ",[28,163,164],{},"delete"," method to try deleting an object's property:",[33,167,169],{"className":35,"code":168,"language":37,"meta":38,"style":38},"var a = 1;\ndelete a; \u002F\u002F false\n",[28,170,171,183],{"__ignoreMap":38},[42,172,173,175,177,179,181],{"class":44,"line":45},[42,174,49],{"class":48},[42,176,53],{"class":52},[42,178,56],{"class":48},[42,180,60],{"class":59},[42,182,63],{"class":52},[42,184,185,187,190],{"class":44,"line":66},[42,186,164],{"class":48},[42,188,189],{"class":52}," a; ",[42,191,192],{"class":79},"\u002F\u002F false\n",[17,194,195,196,198,199,201],{},"You'll see that a variable declared with ",[28,197,49],{}," can't be deleted. So what about ",[28,200,96],{},"?",[33,203,205],{"className":35,"code":204,"language":37,"meta":38,"style":38},"b = 2;\ndelete b; \u002F\u002F true\n",[28,206,207,217],{"__ignoreMap":38},[42,208,209,211,213,215],{"class":44,"line":45},[42,210,129],{"class":52},[42,212,56],{"class":48},[42,214,134],{"class":59},[42,216,63],{"class":52},[42,218,219,221,224],{"class":44,"line":66},[42,220,164],{"class":48},[42,222,223],{"class":52}," b; ",[42,225,226],{"class":79},"\u002F\u002F true\n",[17,228,229,231,232,234,235,242],{},[28,230,96],{}," gets deleted. That's why you should always declare your variables with ",[28,233,49],{}," — otherwise there's a pretty good chance of something going wrong down the line. The ",[236,237,241],"a",{"href":238,"rel":239},"https:\u002F\u002Fdeveloper.mozilla.org\u002Fen-US\u002Fdocs\u002FWeb\u002FJavaScript\u002FReference\u002FStatements\u002Fvar",[240],"nofollow","MDN"," docs mention this too:",[244,245,246],"blockquote",{},[17,247,248],{},"Because of this, you should always declare your variables, whether they are in the global scope or in a function.\nNot declaring a variable will very likely lead to unexpected results. So, in ECMAScript 5 strict mode, assigning to an undeclared variable inside a function throws an error.",[17,250,251],{},"So don't be stubborn about it.",[12,253,255],{"id":254},"references","References",[257,258,259],"ul",{},[260,261,262],"li",{},[236,263,266],{"href":264,"rel":265},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.hexschool.com\u002Fcourses\u002Fjs-core.html",[240],"Hexschool - JavaScript Core (course in Mandarin)",[268,269,270],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sQrFR, html code.shiki .sQrFR{--shiki-default:#BDC4CC}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}",{"title":38,"searchDepth":66,"depth":66,"links":272},[273,274,275],{"id":14,"depth":66,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":66,"text":23},{"id":254,"depth":66,"text":255},"JavaScript","2020-07-26 15:35:31","A quick note on the difference between variables and object properties in JavaScript. Declaring a variable adds a property on window — but so does assigning to an undeclared name like b = 2. The key difference is that a proper variable can't be deleted, while an accidental global one can. Here's why you should always declare your variables.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002Fjs-core-23-objects-variables-vs-object-properties","2",{"title":6,"description":278},false,"en\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjs-core-23-objects-variables-vs-object-properties",[276,289,290],"JavaScript Core","Objects",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F07\u002F26\u002Fjs-core-23-objects-variables-vs-object-properties\u002F","4J9MDyXJts5Rz6qCyMV625okDGHb3rmMXsZF3u9UJT4",{"newer":295,"older":299},{"url":296,"title":297,"date":298},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F07\u002F27\u002Fpixijs-v5-25-dust-particles\u0